how the endpoint gets configured and passed to the AWS SDK.\n\nThe AWS SDK v1 error message \"Failed to connect to service endpoint: \" is generic and doesn't actually include the endpoint URL being attempted, so I can't determine from the error alone what host it's trying to reach. I need to approach this differently—maybe check whether the repository-s3 plugin properly supports HTTP connections to custom endpoints, or investigate whether there's a timing issue with how `path_style_access` gets read from the configuration. I should try a few simpler approaches: setting the endpoint with the full HTTP protocol prefix, or just using the IP address directly instead of the hostname. The ES documentation mentions that custom endpoints for S3-compatible services might need special configuration, particularly around TLS security settings.\n\nLet me dig into the Elasticsearch logs more carefully to see what's actually happening during the connection attempt, since I've already confirmed DNS resolution works. I'm wondering if there's a timeout issue with the repository-s3 plugin when using a custom endpoint—specifically the socket_timeout setting might be too aggressive.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":129,"cache_read_input_tokens":67077,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":129},"output_tokens":32,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5ac5cff4-d409-4ac3-8f10-c278d889fd74","uuid":"a859308f-7015-4364-89a6-694aaba06baf","request_id":"req_011CcLRVfXMspBA5KWFNBvjQ"}
